---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import { loadDroppedCandidates } from "../lib/data.js";
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
const dropped = loadDroppedCandidates();
---
<Base title="Methodology" description="How the Chicago Housing Tracker finds, extracts, and reviews candidate positions.">
  <section class="hero"><h1>Methodology</h1></section>
  <div class="prose">
    <p>
      This tracker records where 2027 Chicago mayoral candidates stand on housing,
      based on what they say in public media — podcasts, interviews, candidate
      forums, and news coverage. It is an accountability tool: every position
      links back to the source it came from.
    </p>

    <h2>How positions get here</h2>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Discovery.</strong> On a schedule, the system scans local-outlet
        news feeds, video and podcast channels, and candidate social posts for new
        appearances.</li>
      <li><strong>Ingestion.</strong> Articles are read as text; videos use their
        captions; audio is transcribed. We store only the extracted quotes and a
        link to the source — not full transcripts or media files.</li>
      <li><strong>Extraction.</strong> An AI model reads the transcript and drafts
        each housing position with the exact supporting quote.</li>
      <li><strong>Review.</strong> A second, independent AI model checks that each
        quote is real and correctly attributed. Then a <em>human</em> reviews and
        approves every position before it appears here.</li>
    </ol>

    <h2>What we do and don't claim</h2>
    <p>
      Summaries are our paraphrase; the linked quote and source are the record.
      A blank cell means a candidate has not addressed that issue on the record
      that we've found — not that they have no view. We track housing closely;
      other issues a candidate raises are noted internally but not published here.
    </p>

    <h2>Under the hood</h2>
    <p>
      For the technically curious: this is a scheduled pipeline that runs on
      GitHub Actions and publishes a static site. Everything is
      <a href="https://github.com/sbahamon/onrecord-chi-mayor-2027">open source</a>,
      and every language-model step is dependency-injected so the whole flow is
      tested offline on fixtures before it ever touches the live models.
    </p>

    <h3>Sources it watches</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>News articles</strong> — direct RSS feeds from Chicago outlets
        (Block Club Chicago, WTTW News, Chicago Reader, The TRiiBE, Chicago
        Sun-Times), read as text with <code>trafilatura</code> behind a real
        browser user-agent. (Google News RSS is kept as a fallback but disabled by
        default — its links are redirects a plain fetch can't read.)</li>
      <li><strong>YouTube</strong> — each candidate's campaign channel plus
        standing channels (WTTW / Chicago Tonight, WGN News, City Club of Chicago),
        via YouTube's per-channel RSS. Audio is pulled with <code>yt-dlp</code>
        and transcribed.</li>
      <li><strong>Podcasts</strong> — Chicago-politics shows (The Ben Joravsky
        Show, The Fran Spielman Show, City Cast Chicago) via their RSS audio
        enclosures. Long episodes are re-encoded to 16&nbsp;kHz mono before
        transcription so they fit the transcription API's upload limit.</li>
      <li><strong>Bluesky</strong> — each candidate's public posts via the
        <code>app.bsky.feed.getAuthorFeed</code> API. The post text is the record
        (no audio); reposts and media-only posts are skipped, and extraction is
        scoped to the account owner so first-person posts are attributed correctly.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      X, Instagram, and TikTok are <em>not</em> auto-tracked (no open feed / terms
      of service), but a link to any of them can still be submitted manually.
    </p>

    <h3>The pipeline</h3>
    <p><code>discover → ingest → extract → propose → review → human approval → publish</code></p>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Discover</strong> polls each source daily, de-duplicates against
        a ledger, and a cheap AI triage call decides whether an item plausibly
        features a candidate discussing policy.</li>
      <li><strong>Ingest</strong> turns the item into clean text — article
        readability, audio&nbsp;→&nbsp;transcript, or a social post's text
        directly. Transcripts are never stored; only the extracted quote and a
        source link are kept (copyright).</li>
      <li><strong>Extract</strong> asks a model to pull each housing position with
        a <em>verbatim</em> quote. Any quote that doesn't literally appear in the
        transcript is dropped, as is any statement about a candidate or topic that
        isn't in our registry.</li>
      <li><strong>Propose</strong> writes the evidence and a draft position and
        opens a pull request.</li>
      <li><strong>Review</strong> — a second, different-family model re-fetches the
        source, re-verifies every quote, and labels the PR verified or flagged.</li>
      <li><strong>Human approval</strong> — nothing publishes automatically; a
        person merges the PR, which rebuilds and redeploys the site.</li>
    </ol>

    <h3>The models</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Extraction &amp; triage:</strong> DeepSeek V3.2
        (<code>deepseek/deepseek-v3.2</code>).</li>
      <li><strong>Independent review:</strong> Moonshot Kimi&nbsp;K2
        (<code>moonshotai/kimi-k2-0905</code>) — deliberately a <em>different</em>
        model family than the extractor, so it catches the extractor's mistakes
        (a common one is attributing an opponent's words to the candidate).</li>
      <li><strong>Transcription:</strong> Whisper large-v3-turbo, via Groq.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Language models are accessed through OpenRouter; the model choices live in a
      config file and can change. The extractor is trusted only to <em>draft</em>:
      a wrong or fabricated quote has to get past a verbatim-quote check, a
      different-family reviewer, and a human before it can reach this site — and
      the auto-publish switch ships off.
    </p>

    {dropped.length > 0 && (
      <>
        <h2>Candidates we don't track</h2>
        <p>
          We focus on candidates with a realistic path in the race. These
          declared candidates are not shown in the matrix; we'll add anyone here
          if that changes or they put a housing position on the record.
        </p>
        <ul>
          {dropped.map((c) => (
            <li>
              <strong>{c.name}</strong>
              {c.drop_reason ? " — " + c.drop_reason : ""}
            </li>
          ))}
        </ul>
      </>
    )}

    <h2>Corrections</h2>
    <p>
      Found a misquote, a wrong attribution, or a missed appearance? Corrections
      are welcome and taken seriously. Please
      <a href="https://github.com/sbahamon/onrecord-chi-mayor-2027/issues/new/choose">open an issue</a>
      — you can also use that form to submit a media link for us to process.
    </p>
  </div>
</Base>
